The paper discusses the ethical and moral obligations of businesses and researchers in designing, deploying, and maintaining machine learning models. It introduces a unified and model-agnostic approach to address issues of robustness, transparency, interpretability, and fairness. These topics are all related to artificial intelligence and machine learning, which suggests that the paper belongs to the cs.AI sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of a genetic algorithm, which is commonly used in machine learning and optimization, further supporting the classification of the paper under cs.AI. The paper also discusses the use of black-box models, which are commonly studied in the cs.LG sub-category. The topics of fairness and ethics suggest that the paper could also belong to the cs.CY sub-category, which focuses on cybersecurity and privacy. The paper also discusses the need for rigorous auditing, which is a topic commonly studied in the cs.CR sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the challenges of managing multiple methods in conjunction with model development, which is a topic commonly studied in the cs.SE sub-category.
